emkornfield commented on issue #3287: ARROW-3133: [C++][WIP] Propose APIs to allow for generic determination of when to preallocate for Kernels
URL: https://github.com/apache/arrow/pull/3287#issuecomment-452607209


   Sorry @xhochy for not responding to your comment.  Per @wesm comment this does not seem to be the preferred approach. 
   
   @wesm Looking into it some more, I think we need some sort of additional metadata to make this work if we want to make use existing infrastructure (i.e. ```detail::InvokeUnaryArrayKernel```).   Some options are:
   
   1.  Define properties of a kernel:
   ```
   struct UnaryKernelProperties {
     /// Will the kernel keep the same null slots.
     bool copies_null_values = false;
   
     // The Kernel's output has the same number of slots as the input
     // (this should potentially could be a virtual function or multiplier instead of a bool).
     bool length_preserving = false;
   
     constexpr int32_t kVariableBitsPerSlot = -1;
     int32_t bits_per_output_slot = kVariableBitsPerSlot;
   };
   ```
   Based on this information InvokeUnaryArrayKernel could try to infer what new buffers need to be allocated (assuming non-nested output types). The same information could potentially be communicated in slightly different forms (e.g. via templates or kernel type hierarchy, but this the struct seems the most straight-forward).  
   
   2.  Provide a new custom allocation function parameter to InvokeUnaryArrayKernel.  Something like:
   ```
   std::function(Status(FunctionContext* ctx, const Datum& input, Datum* out));
   ```
   I think this approach is very similar the one currently proposed in this PR (but I don't think it extends as well to having nodes re-use memory from prior nodes).
   
   @wesm Are either of these appealing to you as an approach or did you have something else in mind?  Would it be better to write something up and share on the mailing list to get feedback (we might need to include some design around the physical execution graph as well to make sure we don't paint ourselves into a corner)?

